# End-of-line policy — deterministic and tool-agnostic (git AND jj).
#
# Rationale: jj's `working-copy.eol-conversion` is a blunt, global switch whose
# behaviour is unreliable per-file (it does not honour these attributes the way
# git does). So we do NOT rely on any checkout-time conversion. Instead the blob
# is the single source of truth: every tool checks the working copy out verbatim.
#   - git : `core.autocrlf` is neutralised by the explicit attributes below.
#   - jj  : `working-copy.eol-conversion` is set to "none" (see docs/eol.md), so
#           the working copy is a byte-for-byte materialisation of the blob.
# The blob therefore carries exactly the bytes we want on disk: LF everywhere,
# except Windows batch launchers, which are stored verbatim with CRLF.

# Default: normalise all text to LF in the repository and check it out as LF.
* text=auto eol=lf

# Windows .cmd launchers are complex multi-line batch programs (labels, goto,
# delayed expansion) that cmd.exe mis-parses with LF line endings. They are the
# only files that must be CRLF. Mark them non-text so NO tool ever rewrites their
# endings; the blob itself is committed with CRLF. Do not change this to
# `text eol=crlf` — that keeps an LF blob and relies on checkout conversion, which
# jj (eol-conversion=none) does not perform, so the working copy would get LF.
*.cmd -text whitespace=cr-at-eol
